It's unnecessary to think of electability as a binary--any given candidate will have an assemblage of traits that, in November 2020, will be seen by voters as positive or negative, and different voters may interpret traits differently. It feels like this question is becoming a coded way of asking "do you think Obama-Trump voters need us to nominate an old white guy?" I don't think age, race, or gender is going to determine who people ultimately vote for, even if some people will walk into the voting booth with prejudices and preconceptions, and even if some people may form negative opinions of someone based on their identity in advance. An electable candidate, I believe, is someone who can communicate a clear vision of what America is and what it can be, who can unite people around that vision, who will tell the truth, admit failure when necessary, listen to people, and tell a story that they will feel included in. They need to inspire people and make them feel heard. I also think an electable candidate needs to have a clear agenda on both international and domestic issues, and I think the best way for them to sell that agenda is to do what Buttigieg and Williamson are doing by emphasizing the values that inform their policies. It's good if they, like Warren or Yang, have specific ideas of how to pay for their plans. Right now, I think it's also important that they are not entrenched in the Washington establishment, since the establishment politics that won elections in the 1990s and the 2000s no longer resonate with people.

In my opinion, good coherent policy that doesn't get too bogged down in the terminology. Obviously, I want the candidate I vote for to have detailed plans so I know that they aren't just saying they'll do something with no idea of how they would accomplish it, but Williamson had a point during the debate when she said Trump didn't win with plans, he won with a slogan. The sad fact of the matter is that she's right - many people who voted for Trump didn't care that none of his plans had concrete details, they just enjoyed that he thought of them at all, or that he was "willing to say things others weren't" (aka willing to be racist). The eventual Democratic candidate needs to be able to sum up their signature policies in a simple way, even though they should have the full details in their heads. Additionally, I know a lot of people think only a straight white man can beat Trump - I disagree. I personally think of the 2020 Democratic candidates, Cory Booker, Kamala Harris, and Pete Buttigieg are among the most "electable." The last thing is I think it will help if the candidate is on the younger side - someone who's had more experience than Mayor Pete, perhaps, but when someone has a long history in public service, that means a lot of possible skeletons in their closet. The shorter time they've been in the public eye, the less possibility for a loaded voting record that will tear apart Democrats before it even gets to the mainstream public.

I don't believe in "electability" as a notion, because it mostly relies on a mistaken assumption of Independants as a mass of the undecided middle, where polling indicates that most independants who lean towards one party or another are mostly disaffected partisans who agree on most issues with their self-identified partisan counterparts. And non-leaning partisans report far lower voting participation, and thus shouldn't be seen as "swing voters". So to the David Brookses of the world "Electability" is "Charisma and Centrism" but in reality, it's a strong ground game and GOTV effort, which isn't really a characteristic of candidates, but their organizations.
